    <div class="illustration-description">
        <h3>Description of the Illustration</h3>
        <p>The image above illustrates a rotating cylinder spacecraft, similar to the one described in Problem 7. It shows a cutaway view of a hollow cylinder with the following key features:</p>
        <ul>
            <li>Outer Diameter: The full width of the cylinder, shown by the outer edge.</li>
            <li>Inner Diameter: Represented by the dashed line inside the cylinder, showing the hollow interior.</li>
            <li>Length: The depth of the cylinder, shown by the perspective view.</li>
            <li>Habitable Volume: The space between the outer and inner diameters (highlighted in light blue), extending the full length of the cylinder. This is the volume we are calculating to determine how many people can comfortably fit in the spacecraft.</li>
        </ul>
        <p>The blue arrows indicate the rotation of the cylinder, which creates artificial gravity for the inhabitants. This rotation is crucial for long-term space habitation but doesn't affect our volume calculation.</p>
    </div>

    

